  "introduction": "Imagine you are calculating the area of a rectangle where the length is 'x' meters and the width is 'x + 2' meters. The area is x(x+2) = x^2 + 2x. This expression, made of variables and numbers with whole number powers, is called a Polynomial. Today, we will learn how to read, classify, and understand these powerful algebraic tools.",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "Polynomials are the building blocks of algebra. They consist of variables raised to non-negative integer powers, combined using addition or subtraction.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Variables must have whole number exponents (0, 1, 2...).",
      "The degree is the highest power of the variable.",
      "Polynomials are classified by degree (Linear, Quadratic, Cubic) and terms (Monomial, Binomial, Trinomial)."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "A polynomial in one variable x can be written as P(x) = a_n x^n + ... + a_1 x + a_0. Here, n is the degree. For example, in 2x^3 - x + 5, the degree is 3 (Cubic). In 4x + 7, the degree is 1 (Linear). Expressions like 1/x or sqrt(x) are NOT polynomials because they involve negative or fractional powers."
  },
